  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD046070",
      "title": "A rapid, tag-free way to purify functional GPCRs",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "A GPCR purification method is described based on how the Galpha-CT (alpha5 helix) interacts with G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs). The importance of this region in binding to and stabilizing the active GPCR state (R*) is well established, as it plays a conserved role in allosterically linking R* binding to G\u03b1 activation. Although only about 20 amino acids, the Galpha-CT contributes approximately 50% of the total interacting surface area with active receptors (R*). Galpha-CT binding also activates the G protein, by triggering conformational changes in the Galpha subunit that facilitate GDP \u2013 GTP exchange and heterotrimer dissociation.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "To purify GPCRs, Galpha-CT was coupled to a chromatography matrix and used as an affinity ligand for GPCR purification. The work focused on rhodopsin and the beta 2 adrenergic receptor (B2AR), but in principle the approach should work for other GPCRs by simply changing the Galpha-CT subtype used for the resin and using receptor-specific ligands. This approach offers several advantages, including the selectivity for properly folded and functional receptors, the ability to purify without the use of a \u201ctag\u201d, and the ability to selectively induce binding or release from the matrix by application of a GPCR-selective ligand.   Purification fractions containing beta2AR-1D4 were analyzed by mass spectrometry as follows: gel bands corresponding to the adrenergic receptor band were excised from a silver-stained gel and pooled for subsequent analysis (lower band raw file). Additionally, gel bands corresponding to the 75 kDa band in fractions 6-8 were excised and analyzed in the same way (upper band raw file). To prepare the gel slices for in-gel digestion with trypsin, they were first shaken for 15 min at room temperature in destaining solution containing freshly made 50 mM sodium thiosulfate, 15 mM potassium ferricyanide; shaken twice in wash buffer containing 25 mM ammonium bicarbonate in 50% acetonitrile for 10 minutes; then dehydrated by addition of acetonitrile (ACN) for 30 seconds and dried in a vacuum centrifuge.  Proteins were trypsinized with ProteaseMax surfactant using the manufacturer\u2019s method (Promega, Catalog # V2071). Samples were reduced and alkylated with 25 mM DTT, 50 mM ammonium bicarbonate at 56C for 20 min, then room temperature incubation in 55 mM iodoacetamide, 50 mM ammonium bicarbonate for 20 min in the dark. Gel slices were washed twice by vortexing in water, shaken twice in wash buffer, then dehydrated and dried. Trypsinization was performed by gel slice rehydration in 20 microliters of digestion buffer containing 12 nanogram/microliter MS grade trypsin (Thermo Scientific Catalog # 90058) in 50 mM ammonium bicarbonate, 0.01% ProteaseMax surfactant (Promega, Catalog # V2071), overlayed with 30 microliters of 0.01% ProteaseMax surfactant, 50 mM ammonium bicarbonate and incubation at 37C for 2 hours. The supernatant was removed and 50 microliters of 1% TFA was added to the gel slice, shaken for 10 min at 37C, and the additional supernatant added.  Each peptide digest was filtered using 0.45-micron Ultrafree MC devices (Millipore, Catalog # UFC30HV00), dried by vacuum centrifugation, and reconstituted in 20 microliters of 5% formic acid.  Peptide digests were analyzed by LC-MS using a Dionex NCS-3500RS UltiMate RSLCnano UPLC system for peptide separation and an Orbitrap Eclipse Tribrid instrument with an EasySpray nano source for mass analysis (Thermo Scientific).  The entire 20 microliters of each peptide digest were injected onto an Acclaim PepMap 100-micron x 2 cm NanoViper C18, 5-micron trap column at a 5 microliters/min flow rate using a loading pump and 2% ACN, 0.1% formic acid solvent. After 5 min of loading and washing, the trap column was connected to a PepMap RSLC C18, 2-micron, 75-micron x 25 cm EasySpray column (Thermo Scientific) using a switching valve.  Peptides were then separated using a 7.5\u201330% ACN gradient over 38 min, and 30-98% ACN gradient over 2 min in a mobile phase containing 0.1% formic acid at a 300 nanoliters/min flow rate.   Survey MS scans from m/z = 375-1500 were collected using the instrument\u2019s Orbitrap mass analyzer at a resolution of 120000, maximum injection time set at auto, normalized automatic gain control (AGC) target at 100%, a run start easy IC internal mass calibration feature activated to achieve precursor mass measurements at below 2 parts per million error, and data collection performed in profile mode. Data-dependent MS/MS spectra were collected in the instrument\u2019s ion trap using collision-induced fragmentation with the following settings: collision energy 35%, quadrupole isolation width 1.6 m/z, dynamic maximum injection time, 20% normalized AGC, MIPS peptide filter, accepted charge states 2-7, and a minimum trigger intensity of 5000. The dynamic exclusion feature was also used with an exclusion duration of 60 sec, mass tolerance of +/- 10 ppm, multiple charge states per precursor allowed, and data collection performed in centroid mode.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "RAW instrument files were processed using Proteome Discoverer version 1.4 (Thermo Scientific), SEQUEST HT software and a UniProt (Swiss Bioinformatics Institute, Geneva, Switzerland) Chlorocelbus sabacus (Green Monkey) database containing 19,526 entries downloaded on 4-13-23 and supplemented with the beta2AR-1D4 adrenergic receptor protein sequence. Searches were configured with a static modification for alkylated cysteines (+57.021 Da), and variable modifications for oxidation of methionine (+15.995 M residues). A parent ion tolerance of 10 ppm, fragment ion tolerance of 0.2 Da, monoisotopic mass calculation, and trypsin cleavage with a maximum of 2 missed cleavages and minimum 6 residue length was used. Searches used a reversed sequence decoy strategy to control peptide false discovery using Percolator software. Results were filtered to remove peptide identifications with q-scores > 0.01 (peptide false discovery less than 1%). The identified protein groups identified were ranked by peptide spectral match numbers (PSMs), and the top 10 non-keratin identified protein groups were reported.",
